"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dmsdbdemp.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"6C6877CC13894C49B7558498E8F4EB2E","order_id":6,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dmshbdemp.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Tangential flow ultrafiltration is used to concentrate large volumes of environmental water samples (<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">e.g.<\/span><span>, wastewater, wastewater-impacted surface waters, etc.) for detection of <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">S. Typhi<\/span><span> and other microorganisms, using molecular methods. This method is applicable for sites with high flow rates, as a large volume is required. Results are quantifiable when enrichment is not used. <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>This method was developed at Emory University, and it has been previously described in the following articles (Liu P et al, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">J Microbiol Methods<\/span><span> 2012; Liu P et al, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">J Appl Micobiology<\/span><span> 2013; Amin N et al<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">, Intern J Hygene Environ Health<\/span><span> 2020).<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>A 40-L grab sample is collected from the source water using a bucket. The sample is brought to the lab and concentrated through a tangential flow ultrafilter. <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">S<\/span><span>. Typhi and S. Paratyphi A are captured on the filter by size exclusion, and eluted in ~500 ml volume of eluant buffer. The eluate is further concentrated by polyethylene (PEG) precipitation. The final pellet is extracted directly for molecular testing. <\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1621624054}